## Slide 4 — Engineering Knowledge

### Core Concepts

| Concept | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| **Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN)** | Deep neural networks with convolutional layers that automatically learn spatial hierarchies (edges → textures → shapes → objects) from image data. Used as the backbone for all food classifiers in NutriSmart. |
| **Transfer Learning** | Re-using a pre-trained network (MobileNetV2 trained on ImageNet's 1.4 M images) and fine-tuning only the top classification layers on domain-specific food datasets. Reduces training time and data requirements by 10×. |
| **Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)** | A two-phase architecture: (1) **Retrieve** relevant documents from a vector database using semantic search, then (2) **Generate** a grounded response with an LLM. Prevents hallucination and allows the chatbot to cite real nutrition data. |
| **Vector Embeddings** | Dense numerical representations of text (here, food descriptions) produced by `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` (384-dim). Semantically similar foods map to nearby vectors, enabling fast nearest-neighbour lookup in ChromaDB. |

### Technologies Used

| Technology | Role in NutriSmart |
|------------|-------------------|
| **Flask** | Lightweight Python web framework powering all routes, REST APIs, authentication, and template rendering. |
| **Keras + TensorFlow** | Deep learning framework for training and inference of ensemble models and the Indian food classifier. |
| **MobileNetV2** | Efficient CNN architecture (3.4 M params) used as the base for transfer-learned food classifiers. Optimised for mobile/edge inference. |
| **YOLOv8 (Ultralytics)** | Real-time object detection model used to locate and crop individual food items on a plate before classification. |
| **ChromaDB** | Open-source vector database storing nutrition embeddings. Supports persistent storage, L2 distance search, and dynamic insertion. |
| **Sentence Transformers** | `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` encodes food descriptions into 384-dim embeddings for semantic search in the RAG pipeline. |
| **Google Gemini Vision API** | Multimodal LLM used as a fallback classifier when local models have low confidence, and as the generative engine for the nutrition chatbot. |
| **scikit-learn** | Random Forest Regressor for personalised daily calorie prediction based on user biometrics. |
| **SQLite** | Embedded relational database for user accounts, daily calorie logs, and cached nutrition data. |
| **EasyOCR** | Optical Character Recognition engine for scanning nutrition labels on packaged food. |

### Algorithms

| Algorithm | Usage |
|-----------|-------|
| **Ensemble Classification** | Three independently trained MobileNetV2 models predict class probabilities; their outputs are **averaged** to produce a more robust final prediction. Reduces variance and improves generalisation. |
| **MobileNetV2 Fine-Tuning** | Pre-trained MobileNetV2 base with frozen early layers; top layers replaced with Dense → Softmax for 96 food classes (Food-101 subset + Indian). Trained with data augmentation (rotation, flip, zoom). |
| **Semantic Search (kNN)** | User queries are encoded with `all-MiniLM-L6-v2`, then matched to the nearest food description vectors in ChromaDB using L2 distance. Top-k results feed the LLM prompt. |
| **Random Forest Regression** | Trained on 10,000 synthetic samples generated from the Mifflin-St Jeor equation. Features: age, height, weight, gender, activity level, goal → predicts daily calorie target. |
| **Mifflin-St Jeor Equation** | Men: BMR = 10W + 6.25H − 5A + 5; Women: BMR = 10W + 6.25H − 5A − 161. Provides the theoretical baseline for calorie prediction. |

